thus in the eleventh chapter of daniel it appears that detailed history of the greek empire in the east from the conquest of alexander to the latter part of the reign of antiochus epiphanes ( verses 3–39 ) , all presented in the form of a prediction , continues with a description ( verses 40–45 ) of events which had not yet taken place but were expected by the writer : the wars which should result in the death of antiochus and the fall of his kingdom ( some modern scholars therefore date the composition of the book to about 167 bce , when antiochus epiphanes sacked jerusalem and desecrated the holy places . )

